        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer19514117" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9199573520685270191">The friendship of Lucy Grealy and Ann Patchett was extraordinary and excruciating. I’ve had some remarkable friendships in my life, but this book forced serious introspection. I identify with Ann, and wonder: could I love someone as broken or needy as Lucy? Would I have the courage to stand up to a self-destructing friend? Do I have the fortitude to stick by a friend through gruesome surgeries/recoveries? Or maybe I am more of Lucy--searching for Perfect Love, drawing others in for my own amusem</span>
  <span id="freeText9199573520685270191" style="display:none">The friendship of Lucy Grealy and Ann Patchett was extraordinary and excruciating. I’ve had some remarkable friendships in my life, but this book forced serious introspection. I identify with Ann, and wonder: could I love someone as broken or needy as Lucy? Would I have the courage to stand up to a self-destructing friend? Do I have the fortitude to stick by a friend through gruesome surgeries/recoveries? Or maybe I am more of Lucy--searching for Perfect Love, drawing others in for my own amusement, masking deep hurts with superficial chaos. So perhaps I am both of Ann and Lucy. <br /><br />I’m not a big fan of the new paperback’s Ya-Ya-Sisterhood cover, but turns out I AM a big fan of author Ann Patchett. (I swear, just when I think I'm hopelessly wed to fiction, a book like this comes along and changes everything...) Above all, this book reaffirmed what I know of friendship—-it makes us in the best of times, and saves us in the worst of times. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="9199573520685270191" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
